04816nam a22007215i 9781512801828DE-B159720210927121507.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210927t20161982pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)980171713  a97815128018287 a10.9783/97815128018282doi  a(DE-B1597)476348  a(OCoLC)979751351  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0360402bisacsh1 aFellman, Anita Clair, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMaking Sense of Self :bMedical Advice Literature in Late Nineteenth-Century America /cMichael Fellman, Anita Clair Fellman.  aReprint 2016 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2016] 4c©1982  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAnniversary Collection00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Making Sense of Self -- t2. The Healthy Self -- t3. The Unhealthy Self -- t4. Brain and Mind in Sickness and in Health -- t5. Making Sense of Sex -- t6. The Rule of Moderation in Sexual Ideology -- t7. The Primacy of the Will -- tConclusion -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSeeking the key to good living through physical well-being, the American public since at least the 1830s has devoured literature proffering medical advice. Making Sense of Self is an historical analysis of the ideological content of a broad sample of late nineteenth-century popular advice literature concerning the body and the mind. At a time when the middle class was threatened with tumultuous social and economic change, such publications offered blueprints for self-regulation, teaching survival and discipline, and bringing some sense of order and hope for self-improvement.Anita and Michael Fellman analyze this literature as a signpost to the general aspirations, anxieties, debates, and assumptions of late Victorian Americans, who were less optimistic than had been their antebellum forebears about personal and social progress. In particular, the authors interpret the ideas these various advisors offered regarding bodily health, the workings of brain and mind, sexuality, and the will. Although the advice literature as a whole was diverse and even contradictory, the ethic of moderation was often stressed as the method, however limited, to obtain some sense of discipline and control, and the will was frequently asserted as the means to a more dynamic self-expression.The sense of fragility, search for security, and dependence on individual self­-governance revealed in this literature remain as persistent elements in the middle-class American character. The significance of this popular ideology lies not in whether it led to specific behavior, but in how it enabled people to interpret themselves and their situation to themselves during a period in which many basic ideological issues appeared more confused than certain. Making Sense of Self offers a close examination of a period analogous to our own times.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aCaregiving.  aHealth.  aMedicine.1 aFellman, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Press Package Archive 1898-1999z978311044252640uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978151280182840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781512801828423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781512801828/original  a978-3-11-044252-6  University of Pennsylvania Press Package Archive 1898-1999c1898d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESS